When [~lwade] hit it he was able to detect something was amiss in the eucanetd logs but the messages were slightly unclear:
{noformat}
2014-04-10 09:07:20  WARN | cluster LWADE_CLU: invalid cluster private_subnet
2014-04-10 09:07:20  WARN | invalid clusters set at idx 0: cannot validate XML
2014-04-10 09:07:20 ERROR | could not validate GNI after XML parse: check network config
{noformat}

Note that in the simple cases (one cluster or clusters with the same configuration) you do not have to specify cluster names at all in the configuration. For example I would use this:

{code}
{
    "InstanceDnsServers": ["10.1.1.254", "8.8.8.8"],
    "PublicIps": [
        "10.104.6.230-10.104.6.255"
    ],
    "PrivateIps": [
        "172.18.0.100-172.18.0.200"
    ]
    "Subnets": [
            "Subnet": {
                "Name": "172.18.0.0",
                "Subnet": "172.18.0.0",
                "Netmask": "255.255.0.0",
                "Gateway": "172.18.0.1"
            }
    ],
    "Clusters": [
    ]
}
{code}

I omitted the default values for the MacPrefix and InstanceDnsDomain but you could specify these at the top level also.

You currently need the empty "Clusters" list due to EUCA-9116.

[~sjones],

I tried the following JSON in a recent test version of 4.0:
{code}
{
    "InstanceDnsServers": ["10.1.1.254", "8.8.8.8"],
    "PublicIps": [
        "10.104.6.230-10.104.6.255"
    ],
    "PrivateIps": [
        "172.18.0.100-172.18.0.200"
    ],
    "Subnets": [
            "Subnet": {
                "Name": "172.18.0.0",
                "Subnet": "172.18.0.0",
                "Netmask": "255.255.0.0",
                "Gateway": "172.18.0.1"
            }
    ],
    "Clusters": [
    ]
}
{code}

I got the following error:

{code}
# euca-modify-property -f cloud.network.network_configuration=/root/network-v2.json
Error(ModifyPropertyValueType): Unexpected character (':' (code 58)): was expecting comma to separate ARRAY entries
{code}

I had to use a previous version where clusters was defined:

{code}
[root@odc-d-31 ~]# euca-modify-property -f cloud.network.network_configuration=/root/network.json
PROPERTY	cloud.network.network_configuration	{
    "InstanceDnsDomain": "eucalyptus.internal",
    "InstanceDnsServers": ["10.1.1.254", "8.8.8.8"],
    "PublicIps": [
        "10.104.6.230-10.104.6.255"
    ],
    "Subnets": [
    ],
    "Clusters": [
        {
            "Name": "GiftOfGab2",
            "MacPrefix": "d0:0d",
            "Subnet": {
                "Name": "172.18.0.0",
                "Subnet": "172.18.0.0",
                "Netmask": "255.255.0.0",
                "Gateway": "172.18.0.1"
            },
            "PrivateIps": [
                "172.18.0.100-172.18.0.200"
            ]
        }
    ]
} was {}
{code}

I am assuming the fix in EUCA-9116 hasn't reached testing branch yet?

Version of Eucalyptus - 4.0.0-0.0.867.20140411git0cd00881.el6

[~hspencer], I had an extra "Subnet": in the example, it should be:

{code}
    "Subnets": [ 
        {
                "Name": "172.18.0.0",
                "Subnet": "172.18.0.0",
                "Netmask": "255.255.0.0",
                "Gateway": "172.18.0.1"
         }
    ],
{code}

The error message tells you exactly where the JSON is invalid. I don't think a better error message is feasible.

An error is now shown when running an instance and a cluster without a subnet configuration is used:

{code}
# euca-run-instances emi-c4a039bd
euca-run-instances: error (InsufficientInstanceCapacity): Networking configuration not found for cluster 'PARTI00'
{code}
